--- GetLogsForScopeByTurn.ps1 ---
GetLogsForScopeByTurn.ps1 is a PowerShell script at the repo root that extracts per-turn log slices for a named scope from bot test output.
Bot logs are structured with "~~~ Turn N ~~~" markers and "Beginning: <Scope>" / "Complete: (...) <Scope>" delimiters.
The script accepts either piped pytest output or a -LogFilePath argument, and always appends any AssertionError/Traceback it finds after the scope block.
The -ScopeName value must match the substring between "Beginning:" and the timing "(...)".

IMPORTANT: simulation tests spawn background threads that keep stdout open, so PowerShell pipe (2>&1 |) will HANG forever waiting for the process to exit.
The correct two-step pattern is:
  Step 1 - capture raw output to file using cmd /c redirect (OS-level, not PowerShell pipe):
    cmd /c ".\.venv\Scripts\python.exe -m pytest Tests/test_Expansion.py::ExpansionTests::test_my_test --tb=short -q -s > raw_test.txt 2>&1"
  Step 2 - process the file through GetLogsForScopeByTurn.ps1:
    Get-Content raw_test.txt | .\GetLogsForScopeByTurn.ps1 -ScopeName "TileIsland update" | Out-File -Encoding utf8 debug_output.txt
  Step 3 - grep across all turns for specific log tokens:
    Get-Content debug_output.txt | Select-String "BACKREF|BUILD_BORDERS|REGISTER_LOOKUP|AssertionError" | ForEach-Object { $_.Line }

The test must have debugMode = False or the sim runs in real-time, taking 20+ seconds and potentially never exiting cleanly.
Do NOT remove enable_search_time_limits_and_disable_debug_asserts() from the test - it suppresses unrelated debug asserts in other subsystems that would crash before you reach the bug under investigation. Instead, re-enable use_debug_asserts on the specific subsystem object after that call if needed.

--- TileIslandBuilder / island debugging tips ---
1. Island unique_id values are NOT stable between test runs unless MapBase.DO_NOT_RANDOMIZE = True is set in the test BEFORE map loading (before both load_map_and_generals and load_map_and_general calls). Always set this when diagnosing island bugs or the IDs in your log statements will shift every run.
2. When adding diagnostic logging to TileIslandBuilder, guard on tile position (e.g. _DIAG_TILES = {(17,10),(17,11)}) rather than unique_id. Position is stable across runs; unique_id is not.
3. There are THREE places tile_island_lookup is written: _register_leaf_island (line ~1077), _break_apart_island_if_too_large (line ~1425), and _build_island_from_tile (line ~1339). When tracing a stale lookup, add a logbook.warning + traceback.format_stack(limit=6) at ALL three write sites guarded by a _DIAG_TILES check, not just one.
4. The "confirmed=False" symptom in BACKREF means island.tile_set and neighbor.tile_set have no adjacent tile pair — most commonly caused by a stale tile_island_lookup entry pointing an unrelated island at a tile it no longer owns, causing _build_island_borders to skip the real neighbor (adjIsland is island → continue).
5. When a new phantom island appears in border_islands, the first question is: what wrote tile_island_lookup for the boundary tile between the two islands incorrectly? Add REGISTER_LOOKUP tracing to find it before making any fix attempts.
6. Full_island parents (island.child_islands is not None) must never be added to refreshIslands in update_tile_islands — they are aggregate containers and _build_island_borders must never be called on them during incremental updates.
7. _update_island_state must NOT clear border_islands early — _build_island_borders uses the old border_islands for its pre-removal pass. Clearing early destroys the neighbor list needed for stale back-ref cleanup.